# Machine-Learning-For-Rent-Prediction
üè† Machine Learning Model for Predicting Rental Prices in the U.S.

A data-driven analysis of U.S. rental prices using exploratory data analysis (EDA), feature engineering, and multiple regression and tree-based machine learning algorithms.
This project identifies the key economic, geographic, and demographic drivers of rent, compares model performance, and builds a predictive system for estimating fair market rental prices.

üìò Project Overview

Rental prices fluctuate due to macro-economic factors, regional dynamics, and housing supply/demand shifts. This project analyzes ~100,000 rental listings across the U.S. to uncover the strongest predictors of rental prices and build a machine learning model capable of estimating rent with high accuracy.

The objective is to help:

Renters understand fair pricing

Property owners set optimal rates

Real estate firms identify profitable markets

Policy makers better understand affordability trends

(See detailed report ‚Üí Rent Prediction Model.pdf) 

Rent Prediction Model

üìä Dataset & Features

The dataset contains economic, spatial, and property-level variables:

Property Features

Square footage

Number of bedrooms

Number of bathrooms

Geospatial Features

Latitude

Longitude

Region (West, Southeast, Northeast, Midwest, South)

Economic & Demographic Features

GDP per capita (by state)

State population

Crime rate

School expenditure per capita

These features were used to identify correlations and build predictive models.

üîç Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)
Key EDA Components

Outlier removal using ¬±3 standard deviations (see page 7 histogram)

Correlation heatmaps for feature relationships

Price distribution by region

Identification of top 20 most expensive states

Geographic visualization of listings across the U.S.

Insight Examples:

Rental prices vary widely by region, with DC, NJ, and RI being the most expensive (pages 18‚Äì19).

GDP per capita and square footage show strong positive correlation with rent (page 21).

Crime rate shows mixed impact depending on region.

ü§ñ Machine Learning Models

Three models were trained and compared:

1Ô∏è‚É£ Polynomial Regression (Degree = 4)

R¬≤ = 0.65

Captures non-linear relationships

No multicollinearity (VIF < 5 for all variables)

2Ô∏è‚É£ Decision Tree Regressor

R¬≤ = 0.75

Feature importance highlights GDP per capita and square footage

Visual tree structure included (page 11)

3Ô∏è‚É£ Random Forest Regressor (Best Model)

R¬≤ = 0.85

Strongest performance with lowest error

Robust to outliers and non-linear patterns

Actual vs. predicted plot (page 15) shows excellent alignment

A comparison table of accuracy is included on page 22 of the PDF.

üìà Winner: Random Forest Regressor

üß† Key Findings
Top Predictors of Rent

Based on feature importance across models:

GDP per capita (strongest driver)

Square footage

Latitude / Longitude (hidden geographic effects)

Crime rate

Population density

Regional Pricing Insights

Northeast and West show the highest median rental prices.

The South and Midwest remain the most affordable regions.

Violent crime rate exhibits a negative correlation with rent in many markets (page 20).

Economic Insight

Higher-GDP regions consistently have higher rent, regardless of population or crime levels.

        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "import seaborn as sns\n",
        "\n",
        "# Load the data\n",
        "df = pd.read_csv(\"Dataset.csv\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Step 1: Filter cities with more than 30 listings\n",
        "city_counts = df['cityname'].value_counts()\n",
        "cities_over_30 = city_counts[city_counts > 30].index\n",
        "filtered_df = df[df['cityname'].isin(cities_over_30)]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Step 2: Remove outliers in price using IQR\n",
        "Q1 = filtered_df['price'].quantile(0.25)\n",
        "Q3 = filtered_df['price'].quantile(0.75)\n",
        "IQR = Q3 - Q1\n",
        "lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR\n",
        "upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR\n",
        "filtered_df = filtered_df[(filtered_df['price'] >= lower_bound) & (filtered_df['price'] <= upper_bound)]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Step 3: Select numerical columns for correlation\n",
        "numerical_cols = [\n",
        "    'price', 'bathrooms', 'bedrooms', 'square_feet',\n",
        "    'GDP Per Capita', 'violent_crime_rate_per_1000',\n",
        "    'school_expenditure_in_1000s', 'population_in_1000s'\n",
        "]\n",
        "data_for_corr = filtered_df[numerical_cols].dropna()\n",
        "\n",
        "# Step 4: Compute correlation matrix\n",
        "corr_matrix = data_for_corr.corr()\n",
        "\n",
        "# Step 5: Plot heatmap\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))\n",
        "sns.heatmap(corr_matrix, annot=True, fmt=\".2f\", cmap='coolwarm', center=0)\n",
        "plt.title('Heatmap of Correlation with Price')\n",
        "plt.tight_layout()\n",
        "plt.show()\n"

        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "# Load the data\n",
        "df = pd.read_csv(\"Dataset.csv\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Filter cities with more than 30 listings\n",
        "city_counts = df['cityname'].value_counts()\n",
        "cities_over_30 = city_counts[city_counts > 30].index\n",
        "filtered_df = df[df['cityname'].isin(cities_over_30)]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Group by city\n",
        "city_stats = filtered_df.groupby('cityname').agg({\n",
        "    'price': 'mean',\n",
        "    'violent_crime_rate_per_1000': 'mean'\n",
        "}).reset_index()\n",
        "\n",
        "# Remove price outliers\n",
        "Q1 = city_stats['price'].quantile(0.25)\n",
        "Q3 = city_stats['price'].quantile(0.75)\n",
        "IQR = Q3 - Q1\n",
        "lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR\n",
        "upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR\n",
        "city_stats_filtered = city_stats[\n",
        "    (city_stats['price'] >= lower_bound) &\n",
        "    (city_stats['price'] <= upper_bound)\n",
        "]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Top 20 cities by price\n",
        "top_20 = city_stats_filtered.sort_values(by='price', ascending=False).head(20)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Plot\n",
        "fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))\n",
        "\n",
        "# Bar plot for Price\n",
        "ax1.bar(top_20['cityname'], top_20['price'], color='steelblue', label='Price ($)')\n",
        "ax1.set_ylabel('Average Price ($)', color='steelblue')\n",
        "ax1.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor='steelblue')\n",
        "ax1.set_xticklabels(top_20['cityname'], rotation=75, ha='right')\n",
        "\n",
        "# Secondary Y-axis for Crime Rate\n",
        "ax2 = ax1.twinx()\n",
        "ax2.plot(top_20['cityname'], top_20['violent_crime_rate_per_1000'], color='red', marker='o', label='Crime Rate')\n",
        "ax2.set_ylabel('Violent Crime Rate (per 1,000)', color='red')\n",
        "ax2.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor='red')\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.title('Average Price and Violent Crime Rate - Top 20 Most Expensive Cities')\n",
        "fig.tight_layout()\n",
        "plt.show()\n",
        "\n"
